Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Boil your #kettle{}. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into quarters. Chop the @carrot{1}(for the gravy) into five chunks (no need to peel!) - use one of the carrots from the bag we've sent you. Chop the @celery stick{1} into four chunks. Pop the veggies in a deep #roasting tray{} with the @chicken drumsticks{2}. Drizzle everything with @olive oil{1%tbsp}, a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Roast on the middle shelf of your oven until everything is nicely browned and crispy, about ~{45-60%minutes}.

In a #measuring jug{}, mix the @chicken stock pots{2} with @water{1.5%l} (amount specified in the ingredient list), stir to dissolve the stock pots and set the stock aside for later.

Remove the tray from your oven. Use a #potato masher{} to slightly break up the veggies and chicken drumsticks, then stir through the @plain flour{50%g} and pour over the stock you made in step 2. Mix together and pop back into your oven for ~{45-60%minutes}, or until the gravy has reduced and thickened nicely. Once nice and thick, drain the gravy through a #sieve{} or #colander{} into a large #mixing bowl{}. Use a large spoon to squeeze out all the meaty juices from the chicken and the veggies. Allow to cool, then cover with #clingfilm{} and refrigerate. Either reserve the veggies and chicken drumsticks to cook our soup recipe later on, or discard.

Chop any tough bottoms off the @Brussels sprouts{400}, cut each sprout in half through the root and then in half again to make quarters. Add to a #bowl{}, cover and refrigerate ready for tomorrow. Quarter the @red cabbage{1} and remove the tough white core (see photo). Slice as thinly as you can. Pop in another bowl, cover and refrigerate. Peel the @red potatoes{1.4%kg} and chop them into 3cm sized chunks. Pop them in a large #saucepan{} of water, ensuring all the potatoes are completely submerged, and cover with a #lid{} or clingfilm. Leave overnight at room temperature. Remove the tops and bottoms from the @carrot{1} and @parsnip{1}. Quarter lengthways and then chop into batons the size of your index finger. Pop in a third large bowl, cover and refrigerate.

== Pigs in Blankets ==

Lay a bacon rasher on a #chopping board{} and then roll a @cocktail sausages{10} up in your @British smoked bacon lardons{60%g}. Repeat with the other sausages. Pop them on a #plate{}, cover with clingfilm and put them in your fridge (you'll cook them with the turkey tomorrow).

== Turkey ==

Preheat your oven to 180C. Pick the rosemary leaves (both the @rosemary{2%sprigs} for the turkey and the potatoes) from their stalks. Discard the stalks and finely chop the leaves. Zest the @lemon{½} with a #fine grater{}. In a #small bowl{}, mix together the lemon zest with half the rosemary and the @olive oil{2%tbsp} (amount specified in the ingredient list), you'll use the remaining rosemary for the potatoes. Drizzle the lemon and rosemary oil over the @turkey{1%for 8-10p}(carcass inside removed) (you can cook it in the tray it came in). Massage the oil over the skin of the turkey. Season with a generous pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Cover the turkey with #foil{} and then pop onto the middle shelf of your oven. Roast the turkey for ~{1%hour} with the foil on. After 1 hour, increase the oven temperature to 200°C, remove and discard the foil and pop the @unsalted butter{45%g} on top of the turkey. Return to the oven for ~{20%minutes} to melt the butter. After 20 mins, remove the turkey from the oven (close the oven door to keep the heat in) and baste the turkey with the melted butter. Tilt the roasting tray and use a large spoon to spoon the butter and juices over the turkey skin. Add the @pigs in blankets{10} to your roasting tray at this point to cook for the remaining ~{40%minutes}. Repeat the basting process every ~{20%minutes}. Total cooking time: 2 hours. Once cooked, remove the turkey and the pigs in blankets from your oven and leave to rest on the side for ~{1.5%hours}, covered tightly with foil.

> TIP: This will make the turkey more moist and will allow you to get everything else cooked stress-free.

== Potatoes ==

While the turkey cooks, pop the large saucepan of potatoes (keeping the water) on high heat, with a generous pinch of @salt{pinch} and bring to the boil. Simmer for about ~{10%minutes}. Mix the remaining chopped @rosemary{}(for the potatoes) with the @plain flour{24%g}, a large pinch of salt and black pepper. Pour the potatoes into a colander and leave for ~{2%minutes} so they drain completely. Dry your large saucepan completely and return the potatoes to it, off the heat. Add the rosemary flour and shake vigorously to 'fluff up' the potatoes and evenly distribute the flour. Leave to one side.

> TIP: By doing this you create more surface area on the potatoes so they go crispier in the oven.

== Red Cabbage ==

Peel the @Bramley apple{1} and then grate on the #coarse grater{}. Halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1} into small ½cm chunks. Melt the @unsalted butter{30%g} in a #wide bottomed saucepan{} over medium heat. Add the red onion and cook until softened, ~{5%minutes}. Stir frequently to make sure it doesn't brown. Add the cabbage, apple, @caster sugar{75%g}, @ground cinnamon{1%tsp}, @star anise{1} and @apple juice{200%ml} to the pan. Stir and bring to the boil, then cover with a lid (or foil). Cook on medium-low heat until the cabbage is completely softened, ~{45%minutes}. Stir every now and then to make sure it is not catching. Remove the lid, increase the heat to medium-high and cook to evaporate any remaining liquid until the cabbage is glossy. Remove the star anise, season with @salt{pinch} and black pepper to taste and then remove from the heat (you'll reheat it later on).

== Potatoes - To Roast ==

Once the turkey is out of the oven, add a really good glug of @vegetable or sunflower oil{} to a large roasting tray - you need the oil to cover the whole bottom of your roasting tray. Pop it in the oven - you want the oil to get really hot so the potatoes cook better. Once the roasting tray has been in your oven for at least ~{10%minutes}, remove it and gently tip the potatoes into it - careful not to burn yourself on any spitting oil! Make sure the potatoes are in an even layer (or they won't get crispy). Roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden and crispy, ~{60-75%minutes}. Turn the potatoes over halfway through cooking. Just cook for a few more mins if they aren't golden in this time.

== Brussels Sprouts ==

Once the root veggies are in the oven, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Add the pancetta to a #frying pan{} with a good splash of oil and cook over a medium-high heat until golden, ~{8-10%minutes}. Reduce the heat in your pancetta pan to medium (pancetta still in the pan!), add the Brussels sprouts and fry for ~{5%minutes}. Now add 3 tbsp of water, cover with a lid and steam-fry until the sprouts are just cooked, ~{6-8%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @double cream{150%ml} and bubble away for ~{3-4%minutes}. Taste and add @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch} if you feel it needs it, then remove from the heat (you'll reheat it just before serving).

== To Serve ==

Carefully transfer the foil covered turkey to a chopping board if you haven't already (reserving any delicious meaty juices), ready to carve. If there is any, the fat on the gravy should have all risen to the top and solidified in the cool, so carefully scrape it off the top and discard. Pour the gravy into a saucepan and bring to a simmer. Bubble away for ~{3-5%minutes}. If you like a thinner gravy stir in a splash of the reserved turkey juices (and a splash of water if you feel it needs it), then bring to the boil. Season to taste. Once piping hot, carefully pour into a #gravy jug{}. You can also reheat the red